=Typology=

See the four-quadrant mapping at the [http://www.gdrc.org/icm/continuum.html Continuum of Informality of Credit] graph:


The essential constituents in the continuum were:

1. '''Informal Suppliers''' or [http://www.gdrc.org/icm/personal.html Personal Credit Suppliers] - those who exhibit fully informal characteristics in their setup. Examples include friends, relatives and neighbours.
   
2. '''[http://www.gdrc.org/icm/formal.html Formal Suppliers]''' - those who exhibit fully formal characteristics, examples include, commercial banks, finance corporations/ companies.
   
3. "Informally-formal" suppliers or '''[http://www.gdrc.org/icm/transactional.html Transactional Credit Suppliers]''' - those who are essentially 'formal' in their setup, but exhibit 'informal' characteristics. Examples include pawn brokers, money lenders and employer credit.
   
4. "Formally-informal" suppliers or [http://www.gdrc.org/icm/mutual.html Mutual Credit Suppliers] - those who are essentially 'informal' in their setup, but exhibit formal characteristics. Examples include Chit funds (ROSCAs), credit societies and people's organizations. 
(http://www.gdrc.org/icm/continuum.html)


